post_text:
Join us in giving a R.O.A.R.ing welcome to Ms. Deb Dillard!

"I'm originally from Bayport, MN and graduated high school from Stillwater High School. After that, I attended and graduated from Minnesota State University - Mankato. I've been teaching for 40 years, primarily in Early Childhood Education, but also lower elementary and Family Literacy.

When I'm not busy teaching, you can find me visiting with my granddaughter, reading, and cooking. I also love meeting and getting to know new people!

This year at Floodwood I will be the long-term Preschool substitute while Ms. Rachel is home with her sweet new baby. I will also be doing the ECFE program this school year. I am most excited for this school year with getting to know the children and their families, along with having children in my classroom in person!"

We're excited to have you apart of our team, Ms. Dillard! If you see her around, make sure to stop and say "hi!"
#PolarPride #FloodwoodSchool #DebDillard

post_text:
Join us in giving a R.O.A.R.ing welcome to Mr. Josh Bestul!

"I grew up in Hibbing, MN and graduated from Hibbing High School in 2013. After graduation, I attended Bemidji State University where I earned my degree in Elementary Education. This will be my third year as a teacher. However, I have worked as a paraprofessional and coached a lot of sports also. This year I will be teaching sixth grade.

When I'm not at Floodwood School, you can find me golfing, hunting, fishing, and spending time at the lake with family and friends.

I'm excited to be joining the staff here at Floodwood School and getting to know the wonderful students, parents and the community! I look forward to getting the opportunity to build relationships with the community as a whole!"

We're excited to have you a part of our team, Mr. Bestul! If you see him around, make sure to say "hi"!
#PolarPride #FloodwoodSchool #JoshBestul

post_text:
You'll be seeing a new smiling face at the front desk this year. Join us in giving a R.O.A.R.ing welcome to Melanie Skripsky!

"I grew up in Appleton, WI and graduated from Appleton North High School. After graduating high school, I packed up and headed down to Fort Myers, Florida to attend Fort Myers Masters Commission.

In 2013, my husband, Joe and I moved back to Floodwood now where we are raising our three kids. When I'm not at Floodwood School, you can find me baking (especially sugar cookies), in my garden, and spending time with my three lovely kids.

I'm excited to be Floodwood Schools new secretary and accomplishing the daily office goals, along with assisting in accounts payable and lunch accounts. I'm excited for fresh starts; a new school year just offers hope and possibilities and I'm looking forward to being a part of that!"

We’re excited to have you a part of our team, Melanie! If you see Melanie, make sure to stop by and say "hi"!
#PolarPride #FloodwoodSchool #MelanieSkripsky

post_text: After planning for 3 options for operating school during the COVID-19 concerns and reviewing the latest MDE and MDH requirements for each, the school board adopted a descriptive learning plan on August 17th. Based on the low number of COVID-19 cases in the district, Floodwood School will be in session 5 full days a week as in the past while taking precautionary measures going above and beyond the requirements. This is one of the many benefits of small class sizes. Families do have the choice to have their students learn from home while streaming the live classroom. Those students must be logged on just as they would be required to be there for class.

post_text:
30 SECOND SPEED TEST
A few months ago we asked our student households and area residents to take a broadband speed test in order to help determine what areas in Minnesota need updating. Now more than ever we need to make sure we have the best speed. Please take this 30 second speed test that will reveal what service you have and if it has adequate bandwidth, especially to support online learning.
Click on this link http://mnruralbroadbandcoalition.com/speedtest.

If you complete your address it makes the results better. If you do not have any internet connection, filling out your address will identify that location on the map with a black dot and that is also important information. The results of the speed test will help secure a broadband connection for our area.

Please share as anyone can take the test. In fact, the more the better. If you have previously taken this speed test, you would not need to do it again, but it will not hurt to do it twice. Thank you!

Be more and better your community with AmeriCorps! Floodwood School has two openings for a 25 hour/week Math tutor and 25 hour/week Reading tutor. Training is provided, but you need to apply soon if you are interested!
The Facebook Live will be broadcast at https://www.facebook.com/MNReadingCorps/ at 6PM tonight to learn more about 1,700 paid opportunities to make a difference in Minnesota.
Whether you are a recent high school grad, college student, parent or retiree, there is an opportunity for you! A year of service with AmeriCorps is a meaningful opportunity to gain experience and make a difference while also earning some awesome perks.
Reading Corps & Math Corps offers:
• Options 25 hours a week at Floodwood School
• Locations throughout Minnesota, including Floodwood
• Start dates in August, September, November and January
• Experience that employers value
You can learn more at readingandmath.net

post_text:
Dear Floodwood Students,

We've reached the end of the school year, and even though the year didn't end like any other year, we couldn't be more proud of your hard work, your resilience and your dedication. We missed ending the school year seeing all of your bright, smiling faces, but know that we are here for you each step of the way, and we look forward to being together again!

To the Class of 2020, congratulations on this accomplishment and milestone. All of us couldn't be more proud. All of your hard work and dedication will help lead you into the next journey that each of you decide to take.

"It's the oldest story in the world. One day you're 17 and planning for someday, and then quietly, without you ever really noticing, someday is today. And that someday is yesterday. And this is your life."

Have a fantastic summer!

From all of us at Floodwood School
#PolarPride #Congratulations #Classof2020

post_text:
I'm a lifelong learner!

That was the theme of the week as we practiced expectations, delved deeper into academic content across subject areas, took risks, made predictions, made (and celebrated) mistakes, improved ideas, increased stamina for rigorous work, intentionally practiced perseverance through very complex tasks, and expanded our community culture.

We are all learners who incorporate our individual strengths and interests to impact the community. This discovery was embedded within a myriad of authentic kindergarten classroom experiences.

We will ALL learn from--and with--each other...together! .

post_text: We are Kind: Kindergarten students learned about bullying and how to be a kind friend during our STEM lab this week. After viewing a video segment, partners discussed how the bullies could show kindness instead. Then, we applied what we discussed with three hands-on STEM building projects: Stacking cups, Keva Planks, and playdough creations. We talked about how we need to be gentle and use helping hands with friends while playing stacking cups. We practiced working together as a strong and skilled team during our Keva building. Finally, we practiced giving and receiving compliments while creating unique artforms out of playdough. K is for Kind!

post_text:
Kindergarten students were challenged this week with the task of using their creativity to develop rules and procedures for math games.

Given nothing more than sets of math materials, students came up with brilliant ideas and persevered through struggles alongside their peers. They were especially good at teaching their games to peers.

So much more learning happens when children have the opportunity to play, use their creativity, and express their learning toward others to aid their understanding.

Way to work, Kindergarten Crew!

post_text:
The kindergarten crew developed core values regarding math workshop this week:

1. We work hard!
2. We make mistakes (because they cause productive struggle, endurance, perseverance, and a growth mindset that helps us learn from misconceptions)!
3. We work together!

Every single activity in our classroom this week addressed at least one of these core values and many addressed all three. We are building a strong foundation for success!
